# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: single-sign-on
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] A **federated identity** in information technology is the means of linking a person's electronic identity and attributes, stored across multiple distinct identity management systems.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Federated identity is related to single sign-on (SSO), in which a user's single authentication ticket, or token, is trusted across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and is understood on the level of technical interoperability, and it would not be possible without some sort of federation.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] In information technology (IT), federated identity management (FIdM) amounts to having a common set of policies, practices and protocols in place to manage the identity and trust into IT users and devices across organizations.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Single sign-on (SSO) systems allow a single user authentication process across multiple IT systems or even organizations.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] SSO is a subset of federated identity management, as it relates only to authentication and technical interoperability.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Centralized identity management solutions were created to help deal with user and data security where the user and the systems they accessed were within the same network – or at least the same "domain of control".
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Increasingly, however, users are accessing external systems which are fundamentally outside their domain of control, and external users are accessing internal systems.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] The increasingly common separation of the user from the systems requiring access is an inevitable by-product of the decentralization brought about by the integration of the Internet into every aspect of both personal and business life.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Evolving identity management challenges, and especially the challenges associated with cross-company, cross-domain access, have given rise to a new approach to identity management, known now as "federated identity management".
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] FIdM, or the "federation" of identity, describes the technologies, standards and use-cases which serve to enable the portability of identity information across otherwise autonomous security domains.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] The ultimate goal of identity federation is to enable users of one domain to securely access data or systems of another domain seamlessly, and without the need for completely redundant user administration.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Identity federation comes in many flavors, including "user-controlled" or "user-centric" scenarios, as well as enterprise-controlled or business-to-business scenarios.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Federation is enabled through the use of open industry standards and/or openly published specifications, such that multiple parties can achieve interoperability for common use-cases.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Typical use-cases involve things such as cross-domain, web-based single sign-on, cross-domain user account provisioning, cross-domain entitlement management and cross-domain user attribute exchange.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Use of identity federation standards can reduce cost by eliminating the need to scale one-off or proprietary solutions.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] It can increase security and lower risk by enabling an organization to identify and authenticate a user once, and then use that identity information across multiple systems, including external partner websites.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] It can improve privacy compliance by allowing the user to control what information is shared, or by limiting the amount of information shared.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] And lastly, it can drastically improve the end-user experience by eliminating the need for new account registration through automatic "federated provisioning" or the need to redundantly login through cross-domain single sign-on.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] The notion of identity federation is extremely broad, and also evolving.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] It could involve user-to-user and user-to-application as well as application-to-application use-case scenarios at both the browser tier and the web services or service-oriented architecture (SOA) tier.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] It can involve high-trust, high-security scenarios as well as low-trust, low-security scenarios.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] The levels of identity assurance that may be required for a given scenario are also being standardized through a common and open Identity Assurance Framework.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] It can involve user-centric use-cases, as well as enterprise-centric use-cases.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] The term "identity federation" is by design a generic term, and is not bound to any one specific protocol, technology, implementation or company.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Identity federations may be bi-lateral relationships or multilateral relationships.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] In the latter case, the multilateral federation frequently occurs in a vertical market, such as in law enforcement (such as the National Identity Exchange Federation - NIEF), and research and education (such as InCommon).
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] If the identity federation is bilateral, the two parties can exchange the necessary metadata (assertion signing keys, etc.) to implement the relationship.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] In a multilateral federation, the metadata exchange among participants is a more complex issue.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] It can be handled in a hub-and-spoke exchange or by the distribution of a metadata aggregate by a federated operator.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] One thing that is consistent, however, is the fact that "federation" describes methods of identity portability which are achieved in an open, often standards-based manner – meaning anyone adhering to the open specification or standard can achieve the full spectrum of use-cases and interoperability.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Identity federation can be accomplished any number of ways, some of which involve the use of formal Internet standards, such as the OASIS Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) specification, and some of which may involve open-source technologies and/or other openly published specifications (e.g.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Information Cards, OpenID, the Higgins trust framework or Novell's Bandit project).
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Technologies used for federated identity include SAML (Security Assertion Markup Language), OAuth, OpenID, Security Tokens (Simple Web Tokens, JSON Web Tokens, and SAML assertions), Web Service Specifications, and Windows Identity Foundation.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] The Federal Risk and Authorization Management Program (FedRAMP) is a government-wide program that provides a standardized approach to security assessment, authorization, and continuous monitoring for cloud products and services.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] The FedRAMP program supports the transition of federal agencies from legacy IT infrastructure to cloud-based computing environments.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Here is a list of services that provide social login features which they encourage other websites to use.
[src:single-sign-on/federated-identity] Related are federated identity login providers.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] The terms "identity management" (IdM) and "identity and access management" are used interchangeably in the area of identity access management.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Identity-management systems, products, applications and platforms manage identifying and ancillary data about entities that include individuals, computer-related hardware, and software applications.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] IdM covers issues such as how users gain an identity, the roles, and sometimes the permissions that identity grants, the protection of that identity, and the technologies supporting that protection (e.g., network protocols, digital certificates, passwords, etc.).
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Identity management (IdM) is the task of controlling information about users on computers.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Such information includes information that authenticates the identity of a user, and information that describes data and actions they are authorized to access and/or perform.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] It also includes the management of descriptive information about the user and how and by whom that information can be accessed and modified.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] In addition to users, managed entities typically include hardware and network resources and even applications.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] The diagram below shows the relationship between the configuration and operation phases of IAM, as well as the distinction between identity management and access management.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Access control is the enforcement of access rights defined as part of access authorization.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Digital identity is an entity's online presence, encompassing personal identifying information (PII) and ancillary information.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] See OECD and NIST guidelines on protecting PII.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] It can be interpreted as the codification of identity names and attributes of a physical instance in a way that facilitates processing.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] A general model of identity can be constructed from a small set of axioms, for example that all identities in a given namespace are unique, or that such identities bear a specific relationship to corresponding entities in the real world.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Such an axiomatic model expresses "pure identity" in the sense that the model is not constrained by a specific application context.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] In general, an entity (real or virtual) can have multiple identities and each identity can encompass multiple attributes, some of which are unique within a given name space.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] The diagram below illustrates the conceptual relationship between identities and entities, as well as between identities and their attributes.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] In most theoretical and all practical models of digital identity, a given identity object consists of a finite set of properties (attribute values).
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] These properties record information about the object, either for purposes external to the model or to operate the model, for example in classification and retrieval.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] A "pure identity" model is strictly not concerned with the external semantics of these properties.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] The most common departure from "pure identity" in practice occurs with properties intended to assure some aspect of identity, for example a digital signature or software token which the model may use internally to verify some aspect of the identity in satisfaction of an external purpose.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] To the extent that the model expresses such semantics internally, it is not a pure model.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Contrast this situation with properties that might be externally used for purposes of information security such as managing access or entitlement, but which are simply stored, maintained and retrieved, without special treatment by the model.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] The absence of external semantics within the model qualifies it as a "pure identity" model.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Identity management can thus be defined as a set of operations on a given identity model, or more generally, as a set of capabilities with reference to it.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] In practice, identity management often expands to express how model content is to be provisioned and reconciled among multiple identity models.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] The process of reconciling accounts may also be referred to as de-provisioning.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] User access enables users to assume a specific digital identity across applications, which enables access controls to be assigned and evaluated against this identity.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] The use of a single identity for a given user across multiple systems eases tasks for administrators and users.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] It simplifies access monitoring and verification, and allows the organizations to minimize excessive privileges granted to one user.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Ensuring user access security is crucial in this process, as it involves protecting the integrity and confidentiality of user credentials and preventing unauthorized access.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Implementing robust authentication mechanisms, such as multi-factor authentication (MFA), regular security audits, and strict access controls, helps safeguard user identities and sensitive data.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] User access can be tracked from initiation to termination of user access.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] When organizations deploy an identity management process or system, their motivation is normally not primarily to manage a set of identities, but rather to grant appropriate access rights to those entities via their identities.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] In other words, access management is normally the motivation for identity management and the two sets of processes are consequently closely related.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Organizations continue to add services for both internal users and by customers.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Many such services require identity management to properly provide these services.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Increasingly, identity management has been partitioned from application functions so that a single identity can serve many or even all of an organization's activities.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] For internal use identity management is evolving to control access to all digital assets, including devices, network equipment, servers, portals, content, applications and/or products.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Services often require access to extensive information about a user, including address books, preferences, entitlements and contact information.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Since much of this information is subject to privacy and/or confidentiality requirements, controlling access to it is vital.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Identity federation comprises one or more systems that share user access and allow users to log in based on authenticating against one of the systems participating in the federation.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] This trust between several systems is often known as a "circle of trust".
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] In this setup, one system acts as the identity provider (IdP) and other systems act as service providers (SPs).
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] When a user needs to access some service controlled by SP, they first authenticate against the IdP.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Upon successful authentication, the IdP sends a secure "assertion" to the SP.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] "SAML assertions, specified using a markup language intended for describing security assertions, can be used by a verifier to make a statement to a relying party about the identity of a claimant.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] In addition to creation, deletion, modification of user identity data either assisted or self-service, identity management controls ancillary entity data for use by applications, such as contact information or location.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Putting personal information onto computer networks necessarily raises privacy concerns.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Absent proper protections, the data may be used to implement a surveillance society.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Social web and online social networking services make heavy use of identity management.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Helping users decide how to manage access to their personal information has become an issue of broad concern.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Research related to the management of identity covers disciplines such as technology, social sciences, humanities and the law.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Decentralized identity management is identity management based on decentralized identifiers (DIDs).
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Within the Seventh Research Framework Programme of the European Union from 2007 to 2013, several new projects related to Identity Management started.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] The PICOS Project investigates and develops a state-of-the-art platform for providing trust, privacy and identity management in mobile communities.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] SWIFT focuses on extending identity functions and federation to the network while addressing usability and privacy concerns and leverages identity technology as a key to integrate service and transport infrastructures for the benefit of users and the providers.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Ongoing projects include Future of Identity in the Information Society (FIDIS), GUIDE, and PRIME.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] In each organization there is normally a role or department that is responsible for managing the schema of digital identities of their staff and their own objects, which are represented by object identities or object identifiers (OID).
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] The organizational policies and processes and procedures related to the oversight of identity management are sometimes referred to as *Identity Governance and Administration* (IGA).
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] How effectively and appropriately such tools are used falls within scope of broader governance, risk management, and compliance regimes.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] An **identity-management system** refers to an information system, or to a set of technologies that can be used for enterprise or cross-network identity management.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] Identity and access management systems are central to meeting regulatory requirements across multiple sectors that mandate controls over who can access sensitive information.
[src:single-sign-on/identity-management] NIST Special Publication 800-53 includes comprehensive identity and access management controls in the AC (Access Control) and IA (Identification and Authentication) control families, providing the reference framework for federal agency IAM implementations.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] For example, a server could generate a token that has the claim "logged in as administrator" and provide that to a client.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] The client could then use that token to prove that it is logged in as admin.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] The tokens can be signed by one party's private key (usually the server's) so that any party can subsequently verify whether the token is legitimate.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] If the other party, by some suitable and trustworthy means, is in possession of the corresponding public key, they too are able to verify the token's legitimacy.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] The tokens are designed to be compact, URL-safe, and usable, especially in a web-browser single-sign-on (SSO) context.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] JWT claims can typically be used to pass identity of authenticated users between an identity provider and a service provider, or any other type of claims as required by business processes.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] JWT relies on other JSON-based standards: JSON Web Signature and JSON Web Encryption.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] Identifies which algorithm is used to generate the signature.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] indicates that this token is signed using HMAC-SHA256.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] JWA (JSON Web Algorithms) RFC 7518 introduces many more for both authentication and encryption.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] Custom claims are usually also included, depending on the purpose of the token.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] and concatenating the two together with a period separator.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] That string is then run through the cryptographic algorithm specified in the header.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] This example uses HMAC-SHA256 with a shared secret (public key algorithms are also defined).
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] , but uses different non-alphanumeric characters and omits padding.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] This resulting token can be easily passed into HTML and HTTP.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] In authentication, when a user successfully logs in, a JSON Web Token (JWT) is often returned.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] This token should be sent to the client using a secure mechanism like an HTTP-only cookie.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] Storing the JWT locally in browser storage mechanisms like local or session storage is discouraged.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] This is because JavaScript running on the client-side (including browser extensions) can access these storage mechanisms, exposing the JWT and compromising security.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] By using this method, the JWT is never exposed to client-side JavaScript; this is the best approach to make use of your JWT while maintaining security best practices.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] When the client wants to access a protected route or resource, the user agent should send the JWT, typically in the `Authorization` HTTP header using the `Bearer` schema.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] This is a stateless authentication mechanism as the user state is never saved in server memory.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] The server's protected routes will check for a valid JWT in the Authorization header, and if it is present, the user will be allowed to access protected resources.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] As JWTs are self-contained, all the necessary information is there, reducing the need to query the database multiple times.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] List of currently registered claim names can be obtained from IANA JSON Web Token Claims Registry.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] JSON web tokens may contain session state.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] But if project requirements allow session invalidation before JWT expiration, services can no longer trust token assertions by the token alone.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] To validate that the session stored in the token is not revoked, token assertions must be checked against a data store.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] This renders the tokens no longer stateless, undermining the primary advantage of JWTs.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] Security consultant Tim McLean reported vulnerabilities in some JWT libraries that used the `alg` field to incorrectly validate tokens, most commonly by accepting a `alg=none` token.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] While these vulnerabilities were patched, McLean suggested deprecating the `alg` field altogether to prevent similar implementation confusion.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] Still, new `alg=none` vulnerabilities are still being found in the wild, with four CVEs filed in the 2018-2021 period having this cause.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] Several JWT libraries were found to be vulnerable to an invalid Elliptic-curve attack in 2017.
[src:single-sign-on/json-web-token] Some have argued that JSON web tokens are difficult to use securely due to the many different encryption algorithms and options available in the standard, and that alternate standards should be used instead for both web frontends and backends.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Generally, the OAuth protocol provides a way for resource owners to provide a client application with secure delegated access to server resources.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] It specifies a process for resource owners to authorize third-party access to their server resources without providing credentials.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Designed specifically to work with Hypertext Transfer Protocol (HTTP), OAuth essentially allows access tokens to be issued to third-party clients by an authorization server, with the approval of the resource owner.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] The third party then uses the access token to access the protected resources hosted by the resource server.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth began in November 2006 when Blaine Cook was developing an OpenID implementation for Twitter.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Meanwhile, Ma.gnolia needed a solution to allow its members with OpenIDs to authorize Mac OS X Dashboard widgets to access their service.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Cook, Chris Messina and Larry Halff from Magnolia met with David Recordon to discuss using OpenID with the Twitter and Magnolia APIs to delegate authentication.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] They concluded that there were no open standards for API access delegation.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] The OAuth discussion group was created in April 2007, for a small group of implementers to write the draft proposal for an open protocol.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] DeWitt Clinton from Google learned of the OAuth project, and expressed his interest in supporting the effort.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] In July 2007, the team drafted an initial specification.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Eran Hammer joined and coordinated the many OAuth contributions creating a more formal specification.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] On 3 October 2007, the OAuth Core 1.0 final draft was released.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] At the 73rd Internet Engineering Task Force (IETF) meeting in Minneapolis in November 2008, an OAuth BoF was held to discuss bringing the protocol into the IETF for further standardization work.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] The event was well attended and there was wide support for formally chartering an OAuth working group within the IETF.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] The OAuth 1.0 protocol was published as RFC 5849, an informational Request for Comments, in April 2010.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Since 31 August 2010, all third party Twitter applications have been required to use OAuth.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] The OAuth 2.0 framework was published considering additional use cases and extensibility requirements gathered from the wider IETF community.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Albeit being built on the OAuth 1.0 deployment experience, OAuth 2.0 is not backwards compatible with OAuth 1.0.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth 2.0 was published as RFC 6749 and the Bearer Token Usage specification as RFC 6750, both standards track Requests for Comments, in October 2012.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] As of November 2024, the OAuth 2.1 Authorization Framework draft is a work in progress.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] It consolidates the functionality in RFCs OAuth 2.0, OAuth 2.0 for Native Apps, Proof Key for Code Exchange, OAuth 2.0 for Browser-Based Apps, OAuth Security Best Current, and Bearer Token Usage.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] On 23 April 2009, a session fixation security flaw in the 1.0 protocol was announced.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] It affects the OAuth authorization flow (also known as "3-legged OAuth") in OAuth Core 1.0 Section 6.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Version 1.0a of the OAuth Core protocol was issued to address this issue.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] In January 2013, the Internet Engineering Task Force published a threat model for OAuth 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Among the threats outlined is one called "Open Redirector"; in early 2014, a variant of this was described under the name "Covert Redirect" by Wang Jing.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth 2.0 has been analyzed using formal web protocol analysis.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] This analysis revealed that in setups with multiple authorization servers, one of which is behaving maliciously, clients can become confused about the authorization server to use and may forward secrets to the malicious authorization server (AS Mix-Up Attack).
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] This prompted the creation of a new best current practice internet draft that sets out to define a new security standard for OAuth 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Assuming a fix against the AS Mix-Up Attack in place, the security of OAuth 2.0 has been proven under strong attacker models using formal analysis.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] One implementation of OAuth 2.0 with numerous security flaws has been exposed.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] In April and May 2017, about one million users of Gmail (less than 0.1% of users as of May 2017) were targeted by an OAuth-based phishing attack, receiving an email purporting to be from a colleague, employer or friend wanting to share a document on Google Docs.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Those who clicked on the link within the email were directed to sign in and allow a potentially malicious third-party program called "Google Apps" to access their "email account, contacts and online documents".
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Within "approximately one hour", the phishing attack was stopped by Google, who advised those who had given "Google Apps" access to their email to revoke such access and change their passwords.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] In the draft of OAuth 2.1 the use of the PKCE (RFC 7636) extension for native apps has been recommended to all kinds of OAuth clients, including web applications and other confidential clients in order to prevent malicious browser extensions from performing OAuth 2.0 code injection attacks.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth framework specifies several grant types for different use cases.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Facebook's Graph API only supports OAuth 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Google supports OAuth 2.0 as the recommended authorization mechanism for all of its APIs.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Microsoft also supports OAuth 2.0 for various APIs and its Azure Active Directory service, which is used to secure many Microsoft and third party APIs.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth can be used as an authorizing mechanism to access secured RSS/Atom feeds.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Access to RSS/ATOM feeds that require authentication has always been an issue.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] For example, an RSS feed from a secured Google Site could not have been accessed using Google Reader.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Instead, three-legged OAuth would have been used to authorize that RSS client to access the feed from the Google Site.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Free software client implementations of the OAuth2 protocol such as the LibreOffice OAuth2OOo extension allows access to remote resources (ie: via the Google API or the Microsoft Graph API and OAuth 2.0) and possibly even with the LibreOffice Basic language.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] This makes it very easy to write and use HTTP requests supporting the OAuth 2.0 protocol in LibreOffice macros.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth is a service that is complementary to and distinct from OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth is unrelated to OATH, which is a reference architecture for authentication, not a standard for authorization.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] However, OAuth is directly related to OpenID Connect (OIDC), since OIDC is an authentication layer built on top of OAuth 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth is also unrelated to XACML, which is an authorization policy standard.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth can be used in conjunction with XACML, where OAuth is used for ownership consent and access delegation whereas XACML is used to define the authorization policies (e.g., managers can view documents in their region).
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth is an *authorization* protocol, rather than an *authentication* protocol.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Using OAuth on its own as an authentication method may be referred to as pseudo-authentication.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] The following diagrams highlight the differences between using OpenID (specifically designed as an authentication protocol) and OAuth for authorization.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] The site sees that the user is not authenticated.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] It formulates a request for the identity provider, encodes it, and sends it to the user as part of a redirect URL.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Once the identity provider is satisfied that the user is sufficiently authenticated, it processes the application's request, formulates a response, and sends that back to the user along with a redirect URL back to the application.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] The application decodes the identity provider's response, and carries on accordingly.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] (OAuth only) The response includes an access token which the application can use to gain direct access to the identity provider's services on the user's behalf.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] The access token acts as a kind of "valet key" that the application can include with its requests to the identity provider, which prove that it has permission from the user to access those APIs.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Because the identity provider typically (but not always) authenticates the user as part of the process of granting an OAuth access token, it is tempting to view a successful OAuth access token request as an authentication method itself.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] However, because OAuth was not designed with this use case in mind, making this assumption can lead to major security flaws.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] XACML is a policy-based, attribute-based access control authorization framework.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] XACML and OAuth can be combined to deliver a more comprehensive approach to authorization.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth does not provide a policy language with which to define access control policies.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] XACML can be used for its policy language.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Where OAuth focuses on delegated access (I, the user, grant Twitter access to my Facebook wall), and identity-centric authorization, XACML takes an attribute-based approach which can consider attributes of the user, the action, the resource, and the context (who, what, where, when, how).
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] XACML provides more fine-grained access control than OAuth does.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth is limited in granularity to the coarse functionality (the scopes) exposed by the target service.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] As a result, it often makes sense to combine OAuth and XACML together where OAuth will provide the delegated access use case and consent management and XACML will provide the authorization policies that work on the applications, processes, and data.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Lastly, XACML can work transparently across multiple stacks (APIs, web SSO, ESBs, home-grown apps, databases...).
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] OAuth focuses exclusively on HTTP-based apps.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Eran Hammer resigned from his role of lead author for the OAuth 2.0 project, withdrew from the IETF working group, and removed his name from the specification in July 2012.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Hammer cited a conflict between web and enterprise cultures as his reason for leaving, noting that IETF is a community that is "all about enterprise use cases" and "not capable of simple".
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] "What is now offered is a blueprint for an authorization protocol", he noted, "that is the enterprise way", providing a "whole new frontier to sell consulting services and integration solutions".
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] In comparing OAuth 2.0 with OAuth 1.0, Hammer points out that it has become "more complex, less interoperable, less useful, more incomplete, and most importantly, less secure".
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] He explains how architectural changes for 2.0 unbound tokens from clients, removed all signatures and cryptography at a protocol level and added expiring tokens (because tokens could not be revoked) while complicating the processing of authorization.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] David Recordon later also removed his name from the specifications for unspecified reasons.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] Dick Hardt took over the editor role, and the framework was published in October 2012.
[src:single-sign-on/oauth] David Harris, author of the email client Pegasus Mail, has criticised OAuth 2.0 as "an absolute dog's breakfast", requiring developers to write custom modules specific to each service (Gmail, Microsoft Mail services, etc.), and to register specifically with them.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OpenID standard provides a framework for the communication that must take place between the identity provider and the OpenID acceptor (the "relying party").
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] An extension to the standard (the OpenID Attribute Exchange) facilitates the transfer of user attributes, such as name and gender, from the OpenID identity provider to the relying party (each relying party may request a different set of attributes, depending on its requirements).
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OpenID protocol does not rely on a central authority to authenticate a user's identity.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Moreover, neither services nor the OpenID standard may mandate a specific means by which to authenticate users, allowing for approaches ranging from the common (such as passwords) to the novel (such as smart cards or biometrics).
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The final version of OpenID is OpenID 2.0, finalized and published in December 2007.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The term *OpenID* may also refer to an identifier as specified in the OpenID standard; these identifiers take the form of a unique Uniform Resource Identifier (URI), and are managed by some "OpenID provider" that handles authentication.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Facebook did use OpenID in the past, but moved to Facebook Connect.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Blogger also used OpenID, but since May 2018 no longer supports it.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID is a decentralized authentication protocol that allows users to authenticate with multiple websites using a single set of credentials, eliminating the need for separate usernames and passwords for each website.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID authenticates a user with an identity provider (IdP), who then provides the user with a unique identifier (called an OpenID).
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] This identifier can then be used to authenticate the user with any website that supports OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] When a user visits a website that supports OpenID authentication, the website will redirect the user to their chosen IdP.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The IdP will then prompt the user to authenticate themselves (e.g., by entering a username and password).
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Once the user is authenticated, the IdP will generate an OpenID and send it back to the website.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The website can then use this OpenID to authenticate the user without needing to know their actual credentials.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID is built on top of several existing standards, including HTTP, HTML, and XML.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID relies on a number of technologies, including a discovery mechanism that allows websites to find the IdP associated with a particular OpenID, as well as security mechanisms to protect against phishing and other attacks.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] One of the key benefits of OpenID is that it allows users to control their own identity information, rather than relying on individual websites to store and manage their login credentials.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] This can be particularly important in cases where websites are vulnerable to security breaches or where users are concerned about the privacy of their personal information.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID has been widely adopted by a number of large websites and service providers, including Google, Yahoo!, and PayPal.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The protocol is also used by a number of open source projects and frameworks, including Ruby on Rails and Django.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The end user interacts with a relying party (such as a website) that provides an option to specify an OpenID for the purposes of authentication; an end user typically has previously registered an OpenID (e.g.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] `alice.openid.example.org`) with an OpenID provider (e.g.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The relying party typically transforms the OpenID into a canonical URL form (e.g.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The `checkid_immediate` mode can fall back to the `checkid_setup` mode if the operation cannot be automated.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] First, the relying party and the OpenID provider (optionally) establish a shared secret, referenced by an *associate handle*, which the relying party then stores.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] If using the `checkid_setup` mode, the relying party redirects the end user's user-agent to the OpenID provider so the end user can authenticate directly with the OpenID provider.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The method of authentication may vary, but typically, an OpenID provider prompts the end user for a password or some cryptographic token, and then asks whether the end user trusts the relying party to receive the necessary identity details.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] If the end user declines the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party with a message indicating that authentication was rejected; the relying party in turn refuses to authenticate the end user.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] If the end user accepts the OpenID provider's request to trust the relying party, then the user-agent is redirected back to the relying party along with the end user's credentials.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] That relying party must then confirm that the credentials really came from the OpenID provider.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In contrast, a *stateless* or *dumb* relying party must make one more background request (`check_authentication`) to ensure that the data indeed came from the OpenID provider.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] After the OpenID has been verified, authentication is considered successful and the end user is considered logged into the relying party under the identity specified by the given OpenID (e.g.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The relying party typically then stores the end user's OpenID along with the end user's other session information.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] To obtain an OpenID-enabled URL that can be used to log into OpenID-enabled websites, a user registers an OpenID identifier with an identity provider.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Identity providers offer the ability to register a URL (typically a third-level domain, e.g. username.example.com) that will automatically be configured with OpenID authentication service.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Once they have registered an OpenID, a user can also use an existing URL under their own control (such as a blog or home page) as an alias or "delegated identity".
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] They simply insert the appropriate OpenID tags in the HTML or serve a Yadis document.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Starting with OpenID Authentication 2.0 (and some 1.1 implementations), there are two types of identifiers that can be used with OpenID: URLs and XRIs.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] XRIs are a new form of Internet identifier designed specifically for cross-domain digital identity.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] For example, XRIs come in two forms—i-names and i-numbers—that are usually registered simultaneously as synonyms.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] I-names are reassignable (like domain names), while i-numbers are never reassigned.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] When an XRI i-name is used as an OpenID identifier, it is immediately resolved to the synonymous i-number (the CanonicalID element of the XRDS document).
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] This i-number is the OpenID identifier stored by the relying party.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In this way, both the user and the relying party are protected from the end user's OpenID identity ever being taken over by another party as can happen with a URL based on a reassignable DNS name.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation (OIDF) promotes and enhances the OpenID community and technologies.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OIDF is a non-profit international standards development organization of individual developers, government agencies and companies who wish to promote and protect OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation was formed in June 2007 and serves as a public trust organization representing an open community of developers, vendors and users.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OIDF assists the community by providing needed infrastructure and help in promoting and supporting adoption of OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] This includes managing intellectual property and trade marks as well a fostering viral growth and global participation in OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OIDF is a global organization to promote digital identity and to encourage the further adoption of OpenID, the OIDF has encouraged the creation of member chapters.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Member chapters are officially part of the Foundation and work within their own constituency to support the development and adoption of OpenID as a framework for user-centric identity on the internet.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OIDF ensures that OpenID specifications are freely implementable therefore the OIDF requires all contributors to sign a contribution agreement.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] This agreement both grants a copyright license to the Foundation to publish the collective specifications and includes a patent non-assertion agreement.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The non-assertion agreement states that the contributor will not sue someone for implementing OpenID specifications.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OpenID trademark in the United States was assigned to the OpenID Foundation in March 2008.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] It had been registered by NetMesh Inc. before the OpenID Foundation was operational.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In Europe, as of August 31, 2007, the OpenID trademark is registered to the OpenID Europe Foundation.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OpenID logo was designed by Randy "ydnar" Reddig, who in 2005 had expressed plans to transfer the rights to an OpenID organization.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Sun Microsystems, VeriSign and a number of smaller companies involved in OpenID have issued patent non-assertion covenants covering OpenID 1.1 specifications.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The covenants state that the companies will not assert any of their patents against OpenID implementations and will revoke their promises from anyone who threatens, or asserts, patents against OpenID implementors.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In March, 2012, a research paper reported two generic security issues in OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Both issues allow an attacker to sign in to a victim's relying party accounts.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] For the first issue, OpenID and Google (an Identity Provider of OpenID) both published security advisories to address it.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Google's advisory says "An attacker could forge an OpenID request that doesn't ask for the user's email address, and then insert an unsigned email address into the IdPs response.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] If the attacker relays this response to a website that doesn't notice that this attribute is unsigned, the website may be tricked into logging the attacker in to any local account." The research paper claims that many popular websites have been confirmed vulnerable, including Yahoo!
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Mail, smartsheet.com, Zoho, manymoon.com, diigo.com.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The researchers have notified the affected parties, who have then fixed their vulnerable code.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] For the second issue, the paper called it "Data Type Confusion Logic Flaw", which also allows attackers to sign in to victims' RP accounts.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Google and PayPal were initially confirmed vulnerable.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID published a vulnerability report on the flaw.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The report says Google and PayPal have applied fixes, and suggest other OpenID vendors to check their implementations.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Some observers have suggested that OpenID has security weaknesses and may prove vulnerable to phishing attacks.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] For example, a malicious relaying party may forward the end user to a bogus identity provider authentication page asking that end user to input their credentials.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] On completion of this, the malicious party (who in this case also controls the bogus authentication page) could then have access to the end user's account with the identity provider, and then use that end user's OpenID to log into other services.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In an attempt to combat possible phishing attacks, some OpenID providers mandate that the end user needs to be authenticated with them prior to an attempt to authenticate with the relying party.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] This relies on the end user knowing the policy of the identity provider.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Other security issues identified with OpenID involve lack of privacy and failure to address the trust problem.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] However, this problem is not unique to OpenID and is simply the state of the Internet as commonly used.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The Identity Provider does, however, get a log of your OpenID logins; they know when you logged into what website, making cross-site tracking much easier.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] A compromised OpenID account is also likely to be a more serious breach of privacy than a compromised account on a single site.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Another important vulnerability is present in the last step in the authentication scheme when TLS/SSL are not used: the redirect-URL from the identity provider to the relying party.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The problem with this redirect is the fact that anyone who can obtain this URL (e.g. by sniffing the wire) can replay it and get logged into the site as the victim user.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Some of the identity providers use nonces (a number used just once) to allow a user to log into the site once and fail all the consecutive attempts.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The nonce solution works if the user is the first one to use the URL.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] However, a fast attacker who is sniffing the wire can obtain the URL and immediately reset a user's TCP connection (as an attacker is sniffing the wire and knows the required TCP sequence numbers) and then execute the replay attack as described above.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Thus nonces only protect against passive attackers, but cannot prevent active attackers from executing the replay attack.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Use of TLS/SSL in the authentication process can significantly reduce this risk.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] On May 1, 2014, a bug dubbed "Covert Redirect related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" was disclosed.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] It was discovered by mathematics doctoral student Wang Jing at the School of Physical and Mathematical Sciences, Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The announcement of OpenID is: "'Covert Redirect', publicized in May 2014, is an instance of attackers using open redirectors – a well-known threat, with well-known means of prevention.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] "The general consensus, so far, is that Covert Redirect is not as bad, but still a threat.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] A patch was not immediately made available.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Ori Eisen, founder, chairman and chief innovation officer at 41st Parameter told Sue Marquette Poremba, "In any distributed system, we are counting of the good nature of the participants to do the right thing.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In cases like OAuth and OpenID, the distribution is so vast that it is unreasonable to expect each and every website to patch up in the near future".
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The original OpenID authentication protocol was developed in May 2005 by Brad Fitzpatrick, creator of popular community website LiveJournal, while working at Six Apart.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Initially referred to as Yadis (an acronym for "Yet another distributed identity system"), it was named OpenID after the openid.net domain name was given to Six Apart to use for the project.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID support was soon implemented on LiveJournal and fellow LiveJournal engine community DeadJournal for blog post comments and quickly gained attention in the digital identity community.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Web developer JanRain was an early supporter of OpenID, providing OpenID software libraries and expanding its business around OpenID-based services.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In late June, discussions started between OpenID users and developers from enterprise software company NetMesh, leading to collaboration on interoperability between OpenID and NetMesh's similar Light-weight Identity (LID) protocol.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The direct result of the collaboration was the Yadis discovery protocol, adopting the name originally used for OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The new Yadis was announced on October 24, 2005.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] After a discussion at the 2005 Internet Identity Workshop a few days later, XRI/i-names developers joined the Yadis project, contributing their Extensible Resource Descriptor Sequence (XRDS) format for utilization in the protocol.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In December, developers at Sxip Identity began discussions with the OpenID/Yadis community after announcing a shift in the development of version 2.0 of its Simple Extensible Identity Protocol (SXIP) to URL-based identities like LID and OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In March 2006, JanRain developed a Simple Registration (SREG) extension for OpenID enabling primitive profile-exchange and in April submitted a proposal to formalize extensions to OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The same month, work had also begun on incorporating full XRI support into OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Around early May, key OpenID developer David Recordon left Six Apart, joining VeriSign to focus more on digital identity and guidance for the OpenID spec.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] By early June, the major differences between the SXIP 2.0 and OpenID projects were resolved with the agreement to support multiple personas in OpenID by submission of an identity provider URL rather than a full identity URL.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Late in 2006, a ZDNet opinion piece made the case for OpenID to users, web site operators and entrepreneurs.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] On January 31, 2007, Symantec announced support for OpenID in its Identity Initiative products and services.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] A week later, on February 6 Microsoft made a joint announcement with JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign to collaborate on interoperability between OpenID and Microsoft's Windows CardSpace digital identity platform, with particular focus on developing a phishing-resistant authentication solution for OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] As part of the collaboration, Microsoft pledged to support OpenID in its future identity server products and JanRain, Sxip, and VeriSign pledged to add support for Microsoft's Information Card profile to their future identity solutions.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In mid-February, AOL announced that an experimental OpenID provider service was functional for all AOL and AOL Instant Messenger (AIM) accounts.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In May, Sun Microsystems began working with the OpenID community, announcing an OpenID program, as well as entering a non-assertion covenant with the OpenID community, pledging not to assert any of its patents against implementations of OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In June, OpenID leadership formed the OpenID Foundation, an Oregon-based public benefit corporation for managing the OpenID brand and property.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The same month, an independent OpenID Europe Foundation was formed in Belgium by Snorri Giorgetti.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] By early December, non-assertion agreements were collected by the major contributors to the protocol and the final OpenID Authentication 2.0 and OpenID Attribute Exchange 1.0 specifications were ratified on December 5.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In mid-January 2008, Yahoo! announced initial OpenID 2.0 support, both as a provider and as a relying party, releasing the provider service by the end of the month.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In early February, Google, IBM, Microsoft, VeriSign and Yahoo! joined the OpenID Foundation as corporate board members.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Around early May, SourceForge, Inc. introduced OpenID provider and relying party support to leading open source software development website SourceForge.net.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In late July, popular social network service MySpace announced support for OpenID as a provider.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In late October, Google launched support as an OpenID provider and Microsoft announced that Windows Live ID would support OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In November, JanRain announced a free hosted service, RPX Basic, that allows websites to begin accepting OpenIDs for registration and login without having to install, integrate and configure the OpenID open source libraries.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In January 2009, PayPal joined the OpenID Foundation as a corporate member, followed shortly by Facebook in February.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OpenID Foundation formed an executive committee and appointed Don Thibeau as executive director.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In March, MySpace launched their previously announced OpenID provider service, enabling all MySpace users to use their MySpace URL as an OpenID.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In May, Facebook launched their relying party functionality, letting users use an automatic login-enabled OpenID account (e.g.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In September 2013, Janrain announced that MyOpenID.com would be shut down on February 1, 2014; a pie chart showed Facebook and Google dominate the social login space as of Q2 2013.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Facebook has since left OpenID; it is no longer a sponsor, represented on the board, or permitting OpenID logins.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In May 2016, Symantec announced that they would be discontinuing their pip.verisignlabs.com OpenID personal identity portal service.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In March 2018, Stack Overflow announced an end to OpenID support, citing insufficient usage to justify the cost.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In the announcement, it was stated that based on activity, users strongly preferred Facebook, Google, and e-mail/password based account authentication.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID is a way to use a single set of user credentials to access multiple sites, while OAuth facilitates the authorization of one site to access and use information related to the user's account on another site.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Although OAuth is not an authentication protocol, it can be used as part of one.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The following drawing highlights the differences between using OpenID versus OAuth for authentication.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Note that with OpenID, the process starts with the application asking the user for their identity (typically an OpenID URI), whereas in the case of OAuth, the application directly requests a limited access OAuth Token (valet key) to access the APIs (enter the house) on user's behalf.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] If the user can grant that access, the application can retrieve the unique identifier for establishing the profile (identity) using the APIs.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID provides a cryptographic verification mechanism that prevents the attack below against users who misuse OAuth for authentication.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Note that the valet key does not describe the user in any way, it only provides limited access rights, to some house (which is not even necessarily the user's, they just had a key).
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Therefore if the key becomes compromised (the user is malicious and managed to steal the key to someone else's house), then the user can impersonate the house owner to the application who requested their authenticity.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] If the key is compromised by any point in the chain of trust, a malicious user may intercept it and use it to impersonate user X for any application relying on OAuth2 for pseudo authentication against the same OAuth authorization server.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Conversely, the notarized letter contains the user's signature, which can be checked by the requesting application against the user, so this attack is not viable.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The letter can use public-key cryptography to be authenticated.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] Published in February 2014 by the OpenID Foundation, OpenID Connect (OIDC) is the third generation of OpenID technology.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] It is an authentication layer on top of the OAuth 2.0 authorization framework.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] It allows computing clients to verify the identity of an end user based on the authentication performed by an authorization server, as well as to obtain the basic profile information about the end user in an interoperable and REST-like manner.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] In technical terms, OpenID Connect specifies a RESTful HTTP API, using JSON as a data format.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] OpenID Connect allows a range of parties, including web-based, mobile and JavaScript clients, to request and receive information about authenticated sessions and end users.
[src:single-sign-on/openid-connect] The OpenID Connect specification is extensible, supporting optional features such as encryption of identity data, discovery of OpenID providers, and session management.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The **S**ecurity **A**ssertion **M**arkup **L**anguage (SAML) is an open standard for exchanging authorization and authentication information.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The *Web Browser SAML/SSO Profile with Redirect/POST bindings* is one of the most common SSO implementation.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This cheatsheet will focus primarily on that profile.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] TLS 1.2 is the most common solution to guarantee message confidentiality and integrity at the transport layer.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Refer to SAML Security (section 4.2.1) for additional information.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] A digitally signed message with a certified key is the most common solution to guarantee message integrity and authentication.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Refer to SAML Security (section 4.3) for additional information.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Assertions may be encrypted via XMLEnc to prevent disclosure of sensitive attributes post transportation.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Refer to SAML Security (section 4.2.2) for additional information.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is a common area for security gaps - see Google SSO vulnerability for a real life example.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Their SSO profile was vulnerable to a Man-in-the-middle attack from a malicious SP (Service Provider).
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SSO Web Browser Profile is most susceptible to attacks from trusted partners.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This particular security flaw was exposed because the SAML Response did not contain all of the required data elements necessary for a secure message exchange.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Following the SAML Profile usage requirements for AuthnRequest (4.1.4.1) and Response (4.1.4.2) will help counter this attack.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Vulnerabilities in SAML implementations due to XML Signature Wrapping attacks were described in 2012, On Breaking SAML: Be Whoever You Want to Be.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is another common area for security gaps simply because of the vast number of steps to assert.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Revisit each security threat that exists within the SAML Security document and assert you have applied the appropriate countermeasures for threats that may exist for your particular implementation.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SAML technical overview contains the most complete diagrams.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] For the Web Browser SSO Profile with Redirect/POST bindings refer to the section 4.1.3.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In fact, of all the SAML documentation, the technical overview is the most valuable from a high-level perspective.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Unsolicited Response is inherently less secure by design due to the lack of **login CSRF** protection.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This limitation arises because the Service Provider (SP) has no opportunity to create a pre-login session or verify that the authentication request was intentionally initiated by the user.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] While this design does not make IdP-initiated SSO uniquely vulnerable to Man-in-the-Middle (MITM) attacks—those risks apply equally to SP-initiated flows if transport security is compromised—it does remove an important layer of login intent validation.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Despite these concerns, IdP-initiated SSO remains supported for backward compatibility (notably with SAML 1.1).
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SAML protocol is rarely the attack vector of choice, though it's important to have cheatsheets to make sure that this is robust.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The various endpoints are more targeted, so how the SAML token is generated and how it is consumed are both important in practice.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Typically the security association between the Identity Provider (IdP) and Service Provider (SP) is created when the SP explicitly chooses to trust the IdP's X.509 signing certificate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Exactly how this occurs can have a strong bearing on overall security posture.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In many cases, the method of manually setting the association is akin to Certificate Pinning, which is not ideal.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Depending on the IdP and SP software, or various design considerations, this may be unavoidable.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Keep in mind that the certificate's signature type can be different from that of the XML document signing type.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The certificate's corresponding private key is the only key that can be used to sign the XML document, but the signing algorithm is chosen at the IdP's discretion.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The most commonly supported signing algorithm is rsa-sha256.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The most common SAML use cases are those of business-to-business (B2B).
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This means that the two parties have different security polices, practices, and risk tolerances.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This guidance focuses mainly on the B2B use case.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] However SAML based federation or SSO is commonly used inside of an organization.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In this case the term third-party CA does not apply.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] It is likely that the CA has been built and run to company standards and it poses no more or less risk to the SAML systems.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The term third-party CA is meant to indicate a private CA run by a third-party.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There are actually 5 separate use cases for certificates in a SAML system.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] While this document mainly talks about the IdP’s SAML signing certificate, the security considerations apply to all four SAML related certificates.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The fifth certificate, the IdP’s TLS server certificate is no more or less special than any other server certificate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is the certificate that an SP uses to validate an IdD’s SAML response.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The IdP signs that response with the certificate’s corresponding private key.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is often the most important certificate and private key, as this protects the identity assertions being sent to the SP.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is less commonly used, as this is used when the SP wants to protect the SAML request sent to the IdP, not just from tampering, but from information disclosure.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There should be no sensitive information in the SAML request, so it is less commonly used.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If used, the certificate and private key must be different from that of the SAML signing certificate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] It is a best practice, though not required, that SPs and IdPs not allow IdP Initiated SSO.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This means that the caller starts their SAML flow at the SP, which produces a signed SAML request intended for the IdP.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] It is a best practice to avoid placing sensitive data in the IdP’s SAML response, but sometimes it is unavoidable.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] When information disclosure is a consideration, an SP will have a SAML encryption certificate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The IdP will use this and the embedded public key, in order to encrypt the SAML response.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SP must use a separate certificate and key pair for SAML signing and encryption.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In the context of SAML signing and encryption, X.509 certificates are most often treated simply as a wrapper to hold a public key that is used to verify a signature, or to wrap a symmetric key for SAML encryption.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Nonetheless, a certificate can contain attributes that can be used to further enhance security.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] OWASP recommends that IdPs and SPs move to adopt the EKU, KU, and key lifetimes mentioned below.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] These legitimately enhance security and allow the verifying party to further protect themselves.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] They also help show compliance with PKI norms.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The key pair size and type and signing algorithm choice has strong bearing on security and interoperability.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Not all IdP and SP software packages or libraries support all combinations of options.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As one IdP often has many SPs associated with it, the only option is to pick the least secure option that is still considered secure.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The most supported and currently secure combination is using RSA 2048 bit keys and SHA-256 hashing/signing.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is referring to the certificate’s signing algorithm and not the SAML XML signing.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As post-quantum algorithms become more prevalent, and ultimately required, this becomes even more complex.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Those writing SAML SP and IdP software should begin looking at options to support more key and signing algorithms.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] ECC Keys can be much smaller while providing more security than RSA keys and the math involved is faster to perform.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] These are preferred when all parties can use them.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] ECC keys can be as low as 256 bit and still be secure.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The minimum RSA key size should be 2048 bit.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] At least one major vendor Microsoft Entra doesn’t support ECC keys.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] When public key cryptography is used for signing data, the data is first hashed with an chosen algorithm and then the hash is signed using the private key.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] No IdP should use SHA-1 as the certificate signing hash.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] That said, if possible moving to larger hash algorithms like SHA-384 or SHA-512 means you are better future-proofing your service.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In this context we are talking about the certificate’s signing algorithm and not the one used to sign the SAML response XML.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Certificates contain a NotBefore and NotOnorAfter attribute.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Most IdPs ignore these in favor of guaranteeing uptime if certificate rotation does not happen on time.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SAML certificate lifetime should be handled well enough that ignoring these is not needed.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Ignoring the certificate's validity period is fundamentally a bad idea.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] 5) allows RSA 2048 bit keys to last for 3 years, the maximum lifetime of a SAML signing certificate should be two years.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If the private key is not well protected, such as in a Hardware Security Module (HSM), that may be too long to be safe.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] EKU describes a specific use case that the certificate is intended for.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] These are use cases like server authentication, client authentication, and code signing, which are not appropriate for SAML signing.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There is no widely accepted EKU for SAML signing, but RFC 9336 defines one that is ideal, id-kp-documentSigning (1.3.6.1.5.5.7.3.36).
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] IdPs and SPs may consider standardizing on this EKU.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] KU describes the underlying cryptographic operations that the private key is meant for.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There are things like digitalSignature, nonRepudiation, keyEncipherment, etc.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] IdPs and SPs may consider requiring digitalSignature and further, disallowing certificates that have other KUs, as certificates should only be used for one use case. e.g. the IdP's TLS server certificate must never be the SAML signing certificate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Certificate Revocation List (CRL) Distribution Point are a list of certificates that the CA says should no longer be trusted.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] They are most often delivered over HTTP and the CRL URLs are generally embedded in each CA issued certificate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The CRL is signed by the CA, so a man-in-the-middle attack against the HTTP cannot harm the integrity of the list, other than to tamper with, and thus invalidate, it.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] That is, it can't be altered by an attacker.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Only CA signed certificates can have a CRL.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If the SAML certificate has a CRL listed, it should be reachable by the validating party and the party should validate it.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Considering the level of risk, if a private key is compromised, and the smaller scale of IdP to SP relationships, parties in a SAML system should establish a plan with contact lists to notify and rotate certificates rapidly in case of an incident.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Many SAML products and libraries don’t support revocation checking, and simply revoking the certificate, without coordinated replacement, means there is an outage.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] OCSP is another way of checking to see if a certificate is revoked.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The OCSP URL is embedded in the certificate , like a CRL, and should be reachable over HTTP.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The response is signed, so MITM attacks are not an integrity concern.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] OCSP is becoming less favored, as the exchange creates privacy concerns.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The caller's IP address can be seen and the certificate that is being used is disclosed.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is less of a concern for SAML, as this does not disclose a destination website, use overall has declined.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If an OCSP URL is present on any certificate in the chain, it should be used to check if the certificate is revoked.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The SAML signing certificate can be signed by one of three things.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The certificate can be self-signed, public CA signed, or private CA signed.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Each has pros and cons, however, given the current state of WebPKI (public) and private PKI, using self-signed SAML certificates are the clear winner when proper precautions are taken for exchanging the certificates.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] All X.509 certificates are signed, using a private key, by an authority known as an Issuer.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This may be a CA or in the case of a self-signed certificate the certificate's corresponding private key.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In the case of a CA signed certificate, the signer may also have a certificate that has an Issuer, and so on.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is called chain, or path, and should terminate in a Root CA (which is self-signed by definition).
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If the issuer is a CA, its attributes, such as EKU, KU, and CRLs, may also be validated.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This should happen for each certificate in the path all the way to the root.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] With this certificate type, a Public CA issues the certificate, in accordance with their rules and the rules of the CA Browser Forum (CABF).
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] These public root CAs get bundled into trust stores maintained by major browser vendors.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Most things on the web trust these, because someone makes sure the trust stores are where they need to be.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] When an IdP rotates its SAML Signing certificate, each SP must simultaneously update its explicit trust of that certificate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This can be challenging with only a few SPs.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This pain has led to the use of SAML signing certificates with the longest possible lifetimes.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This used to be two years with public CAs, then 398 days.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The focus of WebPKI standards and the CABF is on server certificates for TLS.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Recent and ongoing changes in certificate lifetimes make Public CA issued certificates less appealing.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This is because the CABF has a path to making public CA issued certificates last only 47 days.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As the IdP must get the certificate, announce the change for a reasonable amount of time, and then execute the change, this would mean IdPs and SPs would be in a perpetual state of certificate updates.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] It is worth noting that the CABF does not have governance around the use or acquisition of SAML certificates, certificates from their member CAs are what are widely considered Public CAs.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] That is, they are widely trusted by browsers, operating systems, and various development frameworks.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Using Public CA signed certificates allows for revocation checking, which can increase security, but if the certificate exchange is not secured, this could lead to a false sense of security.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As most IdPs and SPs treat the X.509 certificates as an explicit trust, private CAs and PKI could be used.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] How private CAs are designed, built, and run varies wildly and ultimately running CAs well is very costly.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] In order to trust a third-party's CAs, one would need to clearly understand the lifecycle of the CA.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] There are two audit types that would cover this, both of which are very costly, on top of building and running the CAs.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If you rely on third-party CAs, they should be WebTrust, ETSI, or SOC 2 Type II audited.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Trusting third-party CAs, if done improperly, could result in unintended over-trust, for things such as TLS and code signing.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If you choose to trust third-party CAs, make sure they are only trusted for the process of IdP signature validation.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If third-party CAs are used they still should not issue SAML signing certificates where the lifetime of the certificate exceeds that of the underlying key pair, based on guidance from a standards organization such as NIST, NSA, etc..
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If using the strongest private key types, this puts the upper limit at two years.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Due to the explicit nature of most SAML security associations, self-signed certificates are ideal for the use case.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The contents of the certificate and lifetime are not constrained by the policy or process of the issuing CA, be it public or private.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] As rotating SAML certificates can be painful and labor intensive, setting the certificate lifetime as long as safely possible is key.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Few CAs allow long enough lifetimes, due to their focus on the TLS threat model.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If you are using a Hardware Security Module (HSM), follow the vendor's instructions.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The example uses an overly generic distinguished name.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Your Common Name (CN) should be meaningful and specific.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Many IdPs publish a metadata URL that contains basic configuration information including the SAML signing certificate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Many SPs can consume the data from the IdP, updating the Signing certificate information in near real-time.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] This model matches exactly the intent of the Certificate and Public Key Pinning when pinning must be used.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The metadata URL should be protected using TLS where the server certificate comes from a WebPKI CA that is widely trusted and matches the guidance in the Transport Layer Security Cheat Sheet.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] The ideal state of the IdP to SP relationship is that of using the metadata URLs, regardless of what type of certificate is used.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] If metadata URLs are not used, great care must be taken to assure that an attacker does not convince an SP to trust the wrong certificate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Instead, like the metadata URL, present them over properly configured TLS.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] SAML Signing keys are a top security asset and target of attackers.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Great care should be taken when creating the keys and as needed, copying them to nodes of an IdP cluster.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] File based keys are trivial for an attacker with access to exfiltrate.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] IdP operators should strongly consider protecting the private keys using a Hardware Security Module (HSM).
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] HSMs allow an application to use a key without it being exportable or copyable.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] They have mechanisms to safely replicate the keys into a failover HSM, without ever exposing the keys outside of the HSMs.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Quality HSMs would be rated FIPS 140-2 or FIPS 140-3.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Just because SAML is a security protocol does not mean that input validation goes away.
[src:single-sign-on/saml-security-cheat-sheet] Solutions relying cryptographic algorithms need to follow the latest developments in cryptoanalysis.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] An important use case that SAML addresses is web-browser single sign-on (SSO).
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Single sign-on is relatively easy to accomplish within a security domain (using cookies, for example) but extending SSO across security domains is more difficult and resulted in the proliferation of non-interoperable proprietary technologies.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML Web Browser SSO profile was specified and standardized to promote interoperability.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In practice, SAML SSO is most commonly used for authentication into cloud-based business software.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The SAML specification defines three roles: the principal (typically a human user), the identity provider (IdP) and the service provider (SP).
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In the primary use case addressed by SAML, the principal requests a service from the service provider.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider requests and obtains an authentication assertion from the identity provider.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] On the basis of this assertion, the service provider can make an access control decision, that is, it can decide whether to perform the service for the connected principal.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] At the heart of the SAML assertion is a subject (a principal within the context of a particular security domain) about which something is being asserted.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The subject is usually (but not necessarily) a human.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] As in the SAML 2.0 Technical Overview, the terms subject and principal are used interchangeably.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Before delivering the subject-based assertion from Identity Provider to the Service Provider, the Identity Provider may request some information from the principal (such as a user name and password) in order to authenticate the principal.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML specifies the content of the assertion that is passed from the Identity Provider to the Service Provider.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML, one Identity Provider may provide SAML assertions to many Service Providers.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Similarly, one Service Provider (SP) may rely on and trust assertions from many independent Identity Providers (IdP).
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML does not specify the method of authentication at the identity provider.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The IdP may use a username and password, or some other form of authentication, including multi-factor authentication or Kerberos tickets.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] A directory service such as RADIUS or LDAP that allows users to log in with a user name and password is a typical source of authentication tokens at an identity provider.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The popular Internet social networking services also provide identity services that in theory could be used to support SAML exchanges.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Building on these initial contributions, in November 2002 OASIS announced the Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) 1.0 specification as an OASIS Standard.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Meanwhile, the Liberty Alliance, a large consortium of companies, non-profit and government organizations, proposed an extension to the SAML standard called the Liberty Identity Federation Framework (ID-FF).
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Like its SAML predecessor, Liberty ID-FF proposed a standardized, cross-domain, web-based, single sign-on framework.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition, Liberty described a *circle of trust* where each participating domain is trusted to accurately document the processes used to identify a user, the type of authentication system used, and any policies associated with the resulting authentication credentials.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Other members of the circle of trust could then examine these policies to determine whether to trust such information.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] While Liberty was developing ID-FF, the SSTC began work on a minor upgrade to the SAML standard.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting SAML 1.1 specification was ratified by the SSTC in September 2003.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Then, in November of that same year, Liberty contributed ID-FF 1.2 to OASIS, thereby sowing the seeds for the next major version of SAML.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In March 2005, SAML 2.0 was announced as an OASIS Standard.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 represents the convergence of Liberty ID-FF and proprietary extensions contributed by the Shibboleth project, as well as early versions of SAML itself.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Most SAML implementations support v2.0 while many still support v1.1 for backward compatibility.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] By January 2008, deployments of SAML 2.0 became common in government, higher education, and commercial enterprises worldwide.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML has undergone one minor and one major revision since 1.0.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Versions 1.0 and 1.1 of SAML are similar even though small differences exist., however, the differences between SAML 2.0 and SAML 1.1 are substantial.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Although the two standards address the same use case, SAML 2.0 is incompatible with its predecessor.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Although ID-FF 1.2 was contributed to OASIS as the basis of SAML 2.0, there are some important differences between SAML 2.0 and ID-FF 1.2.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, the two specifications, despite their common roots, are incompatible.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML defines XML-based assertions and protocols, bindings, and profiles.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The term *SAML Core* refers to the general syntax and semantics of SAML assertions as well as the protocol used to request and transmit those assertions from one system entity to another.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] *SAML protocol* refers to **what** is transmitted, not **how** (the latter is determined by the choice of binding).
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] So SAML Core defines "bare" SAML assertions along with SAML request and response elements.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML binding* determines how SAML requests and responses map onto standard messaging or communications protocols.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] An important (synchronous) binding is the SAML SOAP binding.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] A *SAML profile* is a concrete manifestation of a defined use case using a particular combination of assertions, protocols and bindings.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML assertions are usually transferred from identity providers to service providers.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Assertions contain *statements* that service providers use to make access-control decisions.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute statement* asserts that a principal is associated with certain attributes.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] An *attribute* is simply a name–value pair.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Relying parties use attributes to make access-control decisions.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] An *authorization decision statement* asserts that a principal is permitted to perform action *A* on resource *R* given evidence *E*.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The expressiveness of authorization decision statements in SAML is intentionally limited.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] More-advanced use cases are encouraged to use XACML instead.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *protocol* describes how certain SAML elements (including assertions) are packaged within SAML request and response elements, and gives the processing rules that SAML entities must follow when producing or consuming these elements.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] For the most part, a SAML protocol is a simple request-response protocol.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important type of SAML protocol request is called a *query*.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] A service provider makes a query directly to an identity provider over a secure back channel.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Thus query messages are typically bound to SOAP.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The result of an attribute query is a SAML response containing an assertion, which itself contains an attribute statement.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] See the SAML 2.0 topic for an example of attribute query/response.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Beyond queries, SAML 1.1 specifies no other protocols.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 expands the notion of *protocol* considerably.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Most of these protocols are new in SAML 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *binding* is a mapping of a SAML protocol message onto standard messaging formats and/or communications protocols.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, the SAML SOAP binding specifies how a SAML message is encapsulated in a SOAP envelope, which itself is bound to an HTTP message.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies just one binding, the SAML SOAP Binding.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In addition to SOAP, implicit in SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO are the precursors of the HTTP POST Binding, the HTTP Redirect Binding, and the HTTP Artifact Binding.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] These are not defined explicitly, however, and are only used in conjunction with SAML 1.1 Web Browser SSO.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The notion of binding is not fully developed until SAML 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 2.0 completely separates the binding concept from the underlying profile.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] A SAML *profile* describes in detail how SAML assertions, protocols, and bindings combine to support a defined use case.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The most important SAML profile is the Web Browser SSO Profile.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] SAML 1.1 specifies two forms of Web Browser SSO, the Browser/Artifact Profile and the Browser/POST Profile.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter passes assertions *by value* whereas Browser/Artifact passes assertions *by reference*.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] As a consequence, Browser/Artifact requires a back-channel SAML exchange over SOAP.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, all flows begin with a request at the identity provider for simplicity.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Proprietary extensions to the basic IdP-initiated flow have been proposed (by Shibboleth, for example).
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The Web Browser SSO Profile was completely refactored for SAML 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Conceptually, SAML 1.1 Browser/Artifact and Browser/POST are special cases of SAML 2.0 Web Browser SSO.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The latter is considerably more flexible than its SAML 1.1 counterpart due to the new "plug-and-play" binding design of SAML 2.0.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Unlike previous versions, SAML 2.0 browser flows begin with a request at the service provider.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] This provides greater flexibility, but SP-initiated flows naturally give rise to the so-called *Identity Provider Discovery* problem, the focus of much research today.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Requirements are often phrased in terms of (mutual) authentication, integrity, and confidentiality, leaving the choice of security mechanism to implementers and deployers.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The primary SAML use case is called *Web Browser Single Sign-On (SSO)*.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] A user utilizes a *user agent* (usually a web browser) to request a web resource protected by a SAML *service provider*.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the requesting user, issues an authentication request to a SAML *identity provider* through the user agent.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The resulting protocol flow is depicted in the following diagram.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The service provider performs a security check on behalf of the target resource.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] If a valid security context at the service provider already exists, skip steps 2–7.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a GET request to the SSO service at the URL from step 2.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] URL query parameter) and performs a security check.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] If the user does not have a valid security context, the identity provider identifies the user (details omitted).
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The user agent issues a POST request to the assertion consumer service at the service provider.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] parameter is taken from the XHTML form at step 4.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The assertion consumer service processes the response, creates a security context at the service provider and redirects the user agent to the target resource.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Since a security context exists, the service provider returns the resource to the user agent.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In SAML 1.1, the flow begins with a request to the identity provider's inter-site transfer service at step 3.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In the example flow above, all depicted exchanges are *front-channel exchanges*, that is, an HTTP user agent (browser) communicates with a SAML entity at each step.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In particular, there are no *back-channel exchanges* or direct communications between the service provider and the identity provider.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Front-channel exchanges lead to simple protocol flows where all messages are passed *by value* using a simple HTTP binding (GET or POST).
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Indeed, the flow outlined in the previous section is sometimes called the *Lightweight Web Browser SSO Profile*.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Alternatively, for increased security or privacy, messages may be passed *by reference*.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] For example, an identity provider may supply a reference to a SAML assertion (called an *artifact*) instead of transmitting the assertion directly through the user agent.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Subsequently, the service provider requests the actual assertion via a back channel.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Such a back-channel exchange is specified as a SOAP message exchange (SAML over SOAP over HTTP).
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] In general, any SAML exchange over a secure back channel is conducted as a SOAP message exchange.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] On the back channel, SAML specifies the use of SOAP 1.1.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] The use of SOAP as a binding mechanism is optional, however.
[src:single-sign-on/security-assertion-markup-language] Any given SAML deployment will choose whatever bindings are appropriate.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] True single sign-on allows the user to log in once and access services without re-entering authentication factors.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] It should not be confused with same-sign on (Directory Server Authentication), often accomplished by using the Lightweight Directory Access Protocol (LDAP) and stored LDAP databases on (directory) servers.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] A simple version of single sign-on can be achieved over IP networks using cookies but only if the sites share a common DNS parent domain.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Conversely, **single sign-off** or **single log-out** (**SLO**) is the property whereby a single action of signing out terminates access to multiple software systems.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] As different applications and resources support different authentication mechanisms, single sign-on must internally store the credentials used for initial authentication and translate them to the credentials required for the different mechanisms.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Other shared authentication schemes, such as OpenID and OpenID Connect, offer other services that may require users to make choices during a sign-on to a resource, but can be configured for single sign-on if those other services (such as user consent) are disabled.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] An increasing number of federated social logons, like Facebook Connect, do require the user to enter consent choices upon first registration with a new resource, and so are not always single sign-on in the strictest sense.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] SSO shares centralized authentication servers that all other applications and systems use for authentication purposes and combines this with techniques to ensure that users do not have to actively enter their credentials more than once.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] The term *reduced sign-on* (RSO) has been used by some to reflect the fact that *single sign-on* is impractical in addressing the need for different levels of secure access in the enterprise, and as such more than one authentication server may be necessary.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] As single sign-on provides access to many resources once the user is initially authenticated ("keys to the castle"), it increases the negative impact in case the credentials are available to other people and misused.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Therefore, single sign-on requires an increased focus on the protection of the user credentials, and should ideally be combined with strong authentication methods like smart cards and one-time password tokens.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Single sign-on also increases dependence on highly-available authentication systems; a loss of their availability can result in denial of access to all systems unified under the SSO.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] SSO can be configured with session failover capabilities in order to maintain the system operation.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Nonetheless, the risk of system failure may make single sign-on undesirable for systems to which access must be guaranteed at all times, such as security or plant-floor systems.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Furthermore, the use of single-sign-on techniques utilizing social networking services such as Facebook may render third party websites unusable within libraries, schools, or workplaces that block social media sites for productivity reasons.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] It can also cause difficulties in countries with active censorship regimes, such as China and its "Golden Shield Project", where the third party website may not be actively censored, but is effectively blocked if a user's social login is blocked.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] In March 2012, a research paper reported an extensive study on the security of social login mechanisms.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] The authors found 8 serious logic flaws in high-profile ID providers and relying party websites, such as OpenID (including Google ID and PayPal Access), Facebook, Janrain, Freelancer, FarmVille, and Sears.com.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Because the researchers informed ID providers and relying party websites prior to public announcement of the discovery of the flaws, the vulnerabilities were corrected, and no security breaches have been reported.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] In May 2014, a vulnerability named Covert Redirect was disclosed.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] It was first reported "Covert Redirect Vulnerability Related to OAuth 2.0 and OpenID" by its discoverer Wang Jing, a Mathematical PhD student from Nanyang Technological University, Singapore.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] In fact, almost all Single sign-on protocols are affected.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Covert Redirect takes advantage of third-party clients susceptible to cross-site scripting (XSS) or open redirect.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] In December 2020, flaws in federated authentication systems were discovered to have been utilized by attackers during the 2020 United States federal government data breach.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Another security issue is that if the session used for SSO is stolen (which can be protected with the HttpOnly cookie flag unlike the SSO token), the attacker can access all the websites that are using the SSO system.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] As originally implemented in Kerberos and SAML, single sign-on did not give users any choices about releasing their personal information to each new resource that the user visited.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] This worked well enough within a single enterprise, like MIT where Kerberos was invented, or major corporations where all of the resources were internal sites.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] However, as federated services like Active Directory Federation Services proliferated, the user's private information was sent out to affiliated sites not under control of the enterprise that collected the data from the user.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Since privacy regulations are now tightening with legislation like the GDPR, the newer methods like OpenID Connect have started to become more attractive; for example MIT, the originator of Kerberos, now supports OpenID Connect.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Single sign-on in theory can work without revealing identifying information such as email addresses to the relying party (credential consumer), but many credential providers do not allow users to configure what information is passed on to the credential consumer.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] As of 2019, Google and Facebook sign-in do not require users to share email addresses with the credential consumer.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] "Sign in with Apple" introduced in iOS 13 allows a user to request a unique relay email address each time the user signs up for a new service, thus reducing the likelihood of account linking by the credential consumer.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Windows environment - Windows login fetches TGT.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Active Directory-aware applications fetch service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Unix/Linux environment - Login via Kerberos PAM modules fetches TGT.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Kerberized client applications such as Evolution, Firefox, and SVN use service tickets, so the user is not prompted to re-authenticate.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Mobile environment - Apple added native Kerberos support in IOS 13.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] On Android a Mobile Device Management service can add support for Kerberos.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Initial sign-on prompts the user for the smart card.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Additional software applications also use the smart card, without prompting the user to re-enter credentials.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Smart-card-based single sign-on can either use certificates or passwords stored on the smart card.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Security Assertion Markup Language (SAML) is an XML-based method for exchanging user security information between an SAML identity provider and a SAML service provider.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] SAML 2.0 supports W3C XML encryption and service-provider–initiated web browser single sign-on exchanges.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] A user wielding a user agent (usually a web browser) is called the subject in SAML-based single sign-on.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] The user requests a web resource protected by a SAML service provider.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] The service provider, wishing to know the identity of the user, issues an authentication request to a SAML identity provider through the user agent.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] The identity provider is the one that provides the user credentials.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] The service provider trusts the user information from the identity provider to provide access to its services or resources.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] A newer variation of single-sign-on authentication has been developed using mobile devices as access credentials.
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] A mobile device is "something you have", as opposed to a password which is "something you know", or biometrics (fingerprint, retinal scan, facial recognition, etc.) which is "something you are".
[src:single-sign-on/single-sign-on] Security experts recommend using at least two out of these three factors (multi-factor authentication) for best protection.
